  "doc_id": "32551",
  "text": "Importantly, the present data clearly support previous research in replicating specific motives; thereby, suggesting that these might be core, higher-order motives of food choice. Specifically, motives revolving around the topics of health and body weight control seem to represent universal motives, at least in Westernized samples. These motives have been found in many previous studies and are represented in various questionnaires such as the Food Choice Questionnaire [CITATION_1] and the Food Choice Motives among Women questionnaire [CITATION_2] as well as in studies using implicit measures [CITATION_3] . Likewise, affect regulation, economic reasons (i.e., price), and convenience aspects appear to emerge in different samples and measures, also suggesting a high reliability as a distinct type of motivation. Furthermore, motives addressed by Jackson and colleagues (2003) and [CITATION_4] , cf., Robinson et al., 2011 , i.e. eating for pleasure, to be sociable, and to meet social norms were supported by the present data.",
